<h2>Hawaii Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Hawaii offers some of the most attractive incentive packages in the nation for solar and energy efficiency improvements. The foundation of these savings comes from the federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC), which provides a 30% tax credit on the total installed cost of solar panel systems through 2032. This credit applies to both the equipment and installation costs, and any unused credit can be carried forward to future tax years. For a typical \$20,000 solar installation, this translates to \$6,000 in federal tax savings.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal 30% Solar Tax Credit (ITC):</strong> Available through 2032, this credit covers 30% of total solar installation costs including equipment, labor, and permitting. The credit steps down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. Homeowners can claim this credit when filing their federal tax return, and unused credits can be rolled over to subsequent years.</li>
<li><strong>Hawaii State Solar Tax Credit:</strong> Hawaii previously offered a state tax credit but discontinued it in 2020. However, existing systems installed before the deadline may still be eligible for remaining credit claims.</li>
<li><strong>Hawaiian Electric Rebate Programs:</strong> HECO offers various rebate programs including the SolarSaver program for battery storage systems, providing rebates up to \$4,250 for qualifying battery installations. They also offer time-of-use rates that can maximize solar savings.</li>
<li><strong>Energy Efficiency Rebates:</strong> Hawaiian Electric provides rebates up to \$5,000 for high-efficiency HVAC systems, heat pump water heaters, and other energy-efficient appliances. These rebates are often stackable with federal tax credits.</li>
<li><strong>Net Energy Metering (NEM):</strong> Hawaii's NEM program allows solar customers to receive credit for excess energy sent back to the grid, though new interconnection rules favor battery storage systems for maximum benefit.</li>
</ul>

